<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06065177 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06065177 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FLORIDA; SCHOOL; BEAUTY; PRODUCT; REGULATION; CONTROVERSY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  In their quest for the perfect do, Broward middle school students are raisingthe dander of school principals.;    Clouds of hair spray in girl's schoolbathrooms have pushed some principals to clear the air with bans on the stickystuff.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HAIR SPRAY TURNING HARD-CORE FOR TEENSCAN GOOD GIRLS STOP AT THE 10-FOOT DO?  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     But students say hard-core users are still smuggling it in.;    &quot;They'reconstantly in the bathroom with hair spray,&quot; said Christine Selvaggi, aseventh-grader at Seminole Middle School in Plantation. &quot;Some kids complainedbecause it leaves a terrible smell in there. We're really not supposed to, buteverybody brings it in.&quot;;    At about one-third of Broward's 29 middleschools, administrators confiscate hair spray when they see it. The latest tojoin the spray-free ranks is Seminole, which started taking away spray thisyear.;    &quot;I spend 30 minutes doing my hair. If you don't get to spray it towhere it will hold, there's no point in doing it in the morning beforeschool,&quot; eighth-grader Shelley Kuntzman said. She uses a non-aerosol spray,because it's not harmful to the environment, but it also doesn't hold as well,so she needs to spray more often.;    Seminole students figure some studentsare allergic to hair spray and can't breathe. On top of that, studentsoccasionally sneak a forbidden smoke in the bathroom, which could be dangerousaround a cloud of hair spray, they said.;    &quot;If someone lights a cigarette inthe bathroom, plus the hair spray, it kind of like explodes,&quot; seventh-graderAnika Omphroy said.;    That theory was news to Cecil Austin, assistantprincipal at Seminole. Administrators were more concerned that students mightspray their classmates, either deliberately or by accident, he said.;    Somestudents continue to stash trial-size bottles in their purses.;    At MargateMiddle School, which has banned hair spray for years, girls sometimes use itoutside, said Lisa Bay, an aide at the school. She said she was not surprisedat the surreptitious squirts. &quot;You know how they're wearing their hair 10 feethigh these days.&quot;;    At Deerfield Beach Middle School, however, spray cloudsare very noticeable, sixth-grader Christine Gordon said, when 15 girls arespraying at once.;    &quot;We're just crammed in there, smooshed in,&quot; Christinesaid. &quot;When you're in the bathroom, you can't breathe a lot.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Fort Lauderdale, Fla.  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910305  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  375  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday March 5, 199100065177,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>